===Noun===
{{rft|order of senses}}
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# The state or quality of being [[true]] to someone or something
#: '''''Truth''' to one's own feelings is all-important in life.''
# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} [[faithfulness|Faithfulness]], [[fidelity]].
#* Samuel Taylor Coleridge
#*: Alas! they had been friends in youth, / But whispering tongues can poison '''truth'''.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A pledge of loyalty or faith.
# True facts, genuine depiction or statements of reality.
#: ''The '''truth''' is that our leaders knew a lot more than they were letting on.''
#* Coleridge
#*: The '''truth''' depends on, or is only arrived at by, a legitimate deduction from all the facts which are truly material.
# Conformity to [[fact]] or [[reality]]; [[correctness]], [[accuracy]].
#* {{quote-magazine|date=2012-01| author=Robert M. Pringle| title=How to Be Manipulative| volume=100| issue=1 |page=31| magazine={{w|American Scientist}}| url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2012/1/how-to-be-manipulative| passage=As in much of biology, the most satisfying '''truths''' in ecology derive from manipulative experimentation. Tinker with nature and quantify how it responds.}}
#: ''There was some '''truth''' in his statement that he had no other choice.''
# Conformity to rule; exactness; close correspondence with an example, mood, model, etc.
#* Mortimer
#*: Ploughs, to go true, depend much on the '''truth''' of the ironwork.
# That which is [[real]], in a deeper sense; spiritual or ‘genuine’ reality.
#: ''The '''truth''' is what is.''
#: ''Alcoholism and redemption led me finally to '''truth'''.''
#* '''1820''', {{w|John Keats}}, ‘Ode on a Grecian Urn’
#*: Beauty is '''truth''', truth beauty, - that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.
# {{cx|countable|lang=en}} Something acknowledged to be true; a true statement or axiom.
#: ''Hunger and jealousy are just eternal '''truths''' of human existence.''
#* '''1813''', {{w|Jane Austen}}, ''{{w|Pride and Prejudice}}''
#*: It is a '''truth''' universally acknowledged, that a single man in possession of a good fortune, must be in want of a wife.
# {{context|physics|dated|lang=en}} [[topness|Topness]]. (See also [[truth quark]].)

